  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "\"Shall\" and \"will\" are both modal verbs used to express future actions or decisions, but they have some differences in usage and connotation.\n\n1. **Formality and Tradition**:\n   - \"Shall\" is traditionally used with the first person (I, we) to indicate a simple future action. It has a more formal tone.\n     - Example: \"I shall go to the store.\"\n   - \"Will\" is used more broadly for all subjects and is the more common choice in modern English.\n     - Example: \"I will go to the store.\"\n\n2. **Intent and Determination**:\n   - In some contexts, \"will\" conveys a strong intention or determination. \n     - Example: \"I will finish this project on time.\"\n   - \"Shall\" can imply an obligation or a suggestion, particularly in legal or formal documents.\n     - Example: \"The party shall provide written notice.\"\n\n3. **Questions and Suggestions**:\n   - \"Shall\" can be used to make offers or suggestions.\n     - Example: \"Shall we dance?\"\n   - \"Will\" is often used in questions regarding willingness.\n     - Example: \"Will you help me with this?\"\n\n4. **Modern Usage**:\n   - In contemporary English, \"will\" is generally preferred over \"shall\" in most situations. \"Shall\" is mostly found in legal contexts, formal documents, or British English.\n\nOverall, while both \"shall\" and \"will\" can indicate future actions, \"will\" is more commonly used in everyday English, whereas \"shall\" tends to carry a more formal or traditional connotation.",
